Apparel is one the largest retail categories, but it's also really tough. F=
ast fashion is a $35 billion segment within a broader apparel and footwear =
market expected to crack $3 trillion this decade -- with a ton of unique ch=
allenges:
Fast Turnover: Clothes are seasonal by nature, and fashions change faster t=
han ever. Many start online, inspired by influencers and celebrities.
Regional tastes: What=E2=80=99s popular in the Middle East (one of Shein=E2=
=80=99s top markets) or South America may have little relation to what=E2=
=80=99s trending in America or Europe.
Huge Variety: A basic t-shirt might come in 10 colors, 6 sizes, and 2 necks=
=2E That=E2=80=99s 120 SKUs for just one product.
Labor intensive: Garment factories aren=E2=80=99t full of robots, they=E2=
=80=99re full of people with sewing machines.
High returns: Items bought online may not fit correctly or look as good on =
someone as they=E2=80=99d hoped, and ecommerce is unable to digitize changi=
ng rooms.=C2=A0
Predicting Demand: A retailer needs to warehouse inventory that accounts fo=
r all of the above, across a huge number of different products.=C2=A0
Fashion is a radically different and inherently challenging product categor=
y. Anyone who can predict demand more accurately, test more nimbly, and dia=
l up production of popular SKUs faster than others, thereby reducing waste,=
 inefficiencies and markdowns, will hold a huge advantage over competitors.=
=C2=A0
